<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 8 — Symbolizing Sentential Logic

  Draft status:
  - Full chapter drafted: sections, chapter summary, key terms,
    and end-of-chapter exercises.
  - Uses Copi notation: ~ (U+007E), \cdot, \lor, \supset, \equiv.
  - Truth tables and proofs are deferred to later chapters.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-symbolizing">

  <title>Symbolizing Sentential Logic</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-symbolizing-intro">
    <p>
      Categorical logic evaluates arguments by understanding how
      subject and predicate terms relate to one another through a quantifier and a copula. Sentential logic evaluates
      arguments by looking at how whole statements are joined
      together. The basic units are not categories such as
      <q>voters</q> and <q>registered people.</q> The basic units
      are complete statements such as <q>The bill passed</q> and
      <q>The governor signed it.</q>
    </p>
    <p>
    Categorical logic is only concerned with the categories things belong or don't belong to. Sentential logic is in many ways much simpler: it doesn't care what anything is. It only cares about statements (insert internal link back to definition of statement in ch. 1) and how they are connected to one another, what someone claimed and how they connected those claims.
    </p>
    <p>
      This chapter teaches the language of sentential logic. We
      will learn how to represent ordinary English statements with
      sentence letters and logical connectives. Later chapters will
      use that symbolic language to build truth tables and natural
      deduction proofs.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-sentential-logic-basic-idea">
    <title>The Basic Idea</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Sentential logic is the logic of compound statements. A
        compound statement is built out of simpler statements using
        words such as <q>not,</q> <q>and,</q> <q>or,</q> <q>if,</q>
        and <q>if and only if.</q>
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-simple-and-compound-statements">
      <title>Simple and compound statements</title>
      <p>
        A <term>simple statement</term> is a statement that we are
        not breaking down any further in sentential logic:
      </p>
      <p>The city approved the permit.</p>
      <p>The protest continued after dark.</p>
      <p>The model passed the test.</p>
      <p>
        A <term>compound statement</term> is built from one or more
        statements using a logical connective:
      </p>
      <p>The city approved the permit <em>and</em> the protest continued after dark.</p>
      <p><em>If</em> the model passed the test, <em>then</em> the company will release it.</p>
      <p>The bill will pass <em>or</em> the committee will delay the vote.</p>
      <p>
        The same English sentence can be simple for one purpose and
        compound for another. <q>The city approved the permit</q>
        contains grammatical parts, but sentential logic treats it
        as one unit unless we need to analyze a logical connective
        inside it. For the most part, however, we'll be breaking things down as far as they go. That is, we'll ask you to reconstruct or translate "in the finest-grained way possible."
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-sentence-letters">
      <title>Sentence letters</title>
      <p>
        We symbolize simple statements with capital letters. The
        letters do not abbreviate individual words; they stand for
        complete statements.
      </p>
      <p>
        Let:
      </p>
      <p><m>P</m> = The city approved the permit.</p>
      <p><m>Q</m> = The protest continued after dark.</p>
      <p>
        Then:
      </p>
      <p><q>The city approved the permit and the protest continued after dark</q> becomes <m>P \cdot Q</m>.</p>
      <p>
        The sentence letter <m>P</m> represents the whole statement
        <q>The city approved the permit.</q> It does not represent
        <q>permit</q> or <q>approved.</q> That distinction matters:
        sentential logic is about whole statements and the
        connectives between them.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-symbolic-tool-conventions">
      <title>Notation and tool conventions</title>
      <p>
        The proof checker and the truth table checker use
        the same notation as this chapter:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><c>~</c> for negation.</p></li>
        <li><p><m>\cdot</m> for conjunction.</p></li>
        <li><p><m>\lor</m> for disjunction.</p></li>
        <li><p><m>\supset</m> for the conditional.</p></li>
        <li><p><m>\equiv</m> for the biconditional.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <table xml:id="table-sentential-connectives-reference">
        <title>Connective Reference</title>
        <tabular>
          <row header="yes">
            <cell>Symbol</cell>
            <cell>Unicode</cell>
            <cell>Typing shortcut</cell>
            <cell>Read as</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><c>~</c></cell>
            <cell>U+007E</cell>
            <cell><c>~</c></cell>
            <cell>not; it is not the case that</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>\cdot</m></cell>
            <cell>U+00B7</cell>
            <cell><c>&amp;</c></cell>
            <cell>and</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>\lor</m></cell>
            <cell>U+2228</cell>
            <cell><c>v</c></cell>
            <cell>or</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>\supset</m></cell>
            <cell>U+2283</cell>
            <cell><c>-&gt;</c></cell>
            <cell>if ... then</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
            <cell>U+2261</cell>
            <cell><c>&lt;-&gt;</c></cell>
            <cell>if and only if</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        The tools also use the same typing shortcuts: <c>-&gt;</c>
        for <m>\supset</m>, <c>&amp;</c> for <m>\cdot</m>, <c>v</c> for
        <m>\lor</m>, <c>&lt;-&gt;</c> for <m>\equiv</m>, and <c>~</c> for
        negation. Atomic statements are capital letters
        <m>A</m>-<m>Z</m>. Parentheses are required around embedded
        connectives, so write <m>A \supset (B \cdot C)</m>, not
        <m>A \supset B \cdot C</m>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-sentential-connectives">
    <title>The Five Connectives</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        This book uses Copi notation. There are five connectives:
        negation, conjunction, disjunction, conditional, and
        biconditional.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-negation">
      <title>Negation</title>
      <p>
        <term>Negation</term> says that a statement is false. We
        write negation with the tilde: <c>~</c>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Let <m>P</m> = The meeting is public.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> = The meeting is not public.
      </p>
      <p>
        Negation attaches to the statement immediately after it.
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> denies <m>P</m>. If the negation applies to a
        larger compound statement, parentheses show that larger
        scope: <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-conjunction">
      <title>Conjunction</title>
      <p>
        <term>Conjunction</term> joins two statements with
        <q>and.</q> We write conjunction with the dot:
        <m>\cdot</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Let <m>P</m> = The meeting is public. Let <m>Q</m> = The
        minutes are posted.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>P \cdot Q</m> = The meeting is public and the minutes are
        posted.
      </p>
      <p>
        English has many ways to express conjunction: <q>and,</q>
        <q>but,</q> <q>although,</q> <q>however,</q> and
        <q>nevertheless</q> often do the same truth-functional work.
        <q>The meeting is public, but the minutes are not posted</q>
        is symbolized <m>P \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>. The word <q>but</q> adds a
        contrast in tone; logically, it still joins two claims. Logic is not interested in the tone, or these shades of meaning. It is only interested in the fact that all these act as conjunctions. They all link two indpendent claims together into one claim. 
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-disjunction">
      <title>Disjunction</title>
      <p>
        <term>Disjunction</term> joins two statements with
        <q>or.</q> We write disjunction with the wedge: <m>\lor</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>P \lor Q</m> = The meeting is public or the minutes are
        posted.
      </p>
      <p>
        In this book, <q>or</q> is <term>inclusive</term> unless a
        passage explicitly says otherwise. <m>P \lor Q</m> means
        <q><m>P</m> or <m>Q</m> or both.</q> If the meeting is public and the
        minutes are posted, the disjunction is true.
      </p>
      <p>
        Ordinary English sometimes uses <q>or</q> exclusively, as
        in <q>You may have soup or salad</q> when the restaurant
        means one but not both. That exclusivity is pragmatic or
        contextual. The default logical connective <m>\lor</m> is
        inclusive.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-conditional">
      <title>Conditional</title>
      <p>
        A <term>conditional</term> joins an antecedent to a
        consequent. We write the conditional with the horseshoe:
        <m>\supset</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>P \supset Q</m> = If <m>P</m>, then <m>Q</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        In <m>P \supset Q</m>, <m>P</m> is the antecedent and <m>Q</m>
        is the consequent. The antecedent is the condition; the
        consequent is what follows if that condition is met.
      </p>
      <p>
        English conditionals are flexible. Each of the following
        has the same basic conditional structure:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>If the storm reaches campus, then labs will be canceled.</p></li>
        <li><p>Labs will be canceled if the storm reaches campus.</p></li>
        <li><p>The storm reaching campus is sufficient for labs to be canceled.</p></li>
        <li><p>Labs being canceled is necessary for the storm to reach campus.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        In each case, if <m>P</m> = the storm reaches campus and
        <m>Q</m> = labs will be canceled, the symbolization is
        <m>P \supset Q</m>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-biconditional">
      <title>Biconditional</title>
      <p>
        A <term>biconditional</term> says that two statements stand
        or fall together. We write the biconditional with the triple
        bar: <m>\equiv</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>P \equiv Q</m> = <m>P</m> if and only if <m>Q</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>If and only if</q> means both directions: if <m>P</m> then <m>Q</m>,
        and if <m>Q</m> then <m>P</m>. So <m>P \equiv Q</m> is equivalent to
        <m>(P \supset Q) \cdot (Q \supset P)</m>. In ordinary prose, phrases such
        as <q>just in case</q> and <q>exactly when</q> often signal
        a biconditional.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-main-connective-and-scope">
    <title>Main Connective and Scope</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Once a symbolic statement gets longer than one connective,
        parentheses become essential. They tell us which connective
        governs the whole statement.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-main-connective">
      <title>Main connective</title>
      <p>
        The <term>main connective</term> is the connective that
        governs the whole compound statement. It tells us the
        statement's overall logical form.
      </p>
      <p>
        In <m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m>, the main connective is <m>\supset</m>.
        The whole statement is a conditional. Its antecedent is
        <m>P \cdot Q</m>, and its consequent is <m>R</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        In <m>P \cdot (Q \supset R)</m>, the main connective is <m>\cdot</m>.
        The whole statement is a conjunction. Its left conjunct is
        <m>P</m>, and its right conjunct is <m>Q \supset R</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        These two formulas contain the same letters and the same
        connectives, but they say different things. Parentheses are
        not decoration. They are part of the statement.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-scope">
      <title>Scope</title>
      <p>
        The <term>scope</term> of a connective is the part of the
        formula governed by that connective. Negation makes this
        especially clear.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \cdot Q</m> says: <m>P</m> is false, and <m>Q</m> is true.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m> says: it is not the case that both <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>
        are true.
      </p>
      <p>
        Those are not equivalent. If <m>P</m> is true and <m>Q</m> is false, then
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \cdot Q</m> is false, but <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m> is true.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-formation-rules">
      <title>Formation rules</title>
      <p>
        A symbolic statement has to be well formed. Use these rules:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>A capital letter by itself is a statement: <m>P</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>If <m>P</m> is a statement, then <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> is a statement.</p></li>
        <li><p>If <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are statements, then <m>(P \cdot Q)</m>, <m>(P \lor Q)</m>, <m>(P \supset Q)</m>, and <m>(P \equiv Q)</m> are statements.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        In practice, we often omit the outermost parentheses when
        the formula is clear. We write <m>P \cdot Q</m> instead of
        <m>(P \cdot Q)</m>. But we keep internal parentheses whenever
        leaving them out would make the structure unclear:
        <m>P \supset (Q \cdot R)</m>, not <m>P \supset Q \cdot R</m>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-symbolizing-conditionals">
    <title>Conditionals in English</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Conditionals cause more symbolization mistakes than any
        other connective. The problem is not the symbol; the
        problem is ordinary English.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-if-and-only-if">
      <title>If, only if, and if and only if</title>
      <p>
        The word <q>if</q> introduces a sufficient condition. In
        the standard form <q>If <m>P</m>, then <m>Q</m>,</q> <m>P</m> is sufficient for
        <m>Q</m>. Symbolically: <m>P \supset Q</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The phrase <q>only if</q> introduces a necessary condition.
        <q><m>P</m> only if <m>Q</m></q> means that <m>Q</m> is required for <m>P</m>. If <m>P</m> is
        true, <m>Q</m> must be true. Symbolically: <m>P \supset Q</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the pattern students most often reverse:
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>The server restarts only if the update installs</q>
        becomes <m>R \supset U</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The update installing is necessary for the restart. The
        restart is enough to guarantee that the update installed.
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>If and only if</q> gives both directions:
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>The server restarts if and only if the update installs</q>
        becomes <m>R \equiv U</m>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-unless">
      <title>Unless</title>
      <p>
        <q>Unless</q> usually means <q>if not.</q> The sentence
        <q>The hearing will proceed unless the judge grants a
        delay</q> can be read:
      </p>
      <p>
        If the judge does not grant a delay, then the hearing will
        proceed.
      </p>
      <p>
        Let <m>D</m> = the judge grants a delay. Let <m>H</m> = the
        hearing will proceed. The symbolization is:
      </p>
      <p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}D \supset H</m></p>
      <p>
        In many contexts, <q><m>P</m> unless <m>Q</m></q> also suggests that if <m>Q</m>
        happens, <m>P</m> will not happen. That stronger reading is often
        a conversational implication, not part of the minimal
        logical form. When the stronger reading is clearly intended,
        symbolize it explicitly as a biconditional or as a
        conjunction of two conditionals.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-neither-nor">
      <title>Neither/nor</title>
      <p>
        <q>Neither <m>P</m> nor <m>Q</m></q> means both <m>P</m> is false and <m>Q</m> is false:
      </p>
      <p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></p>
      <p>
        It is also equivalent to <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \lor Q)</m>. The first version
        is usually easier for beginners to read.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-symbolizing-arguments">
    <title>Symbolizing Arguments</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Symbolizing a sentence is useful. Symbolizing an argument
        is where sentential logic starts to pay off.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-symbolized-standard-form">
      <title>Standard form, again</title>
      <p>
        The standard-form habit from Chapter 1 still matters. Put
        each premise on its own line, put the conclusion last, and
        use a symbolization key.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-symbolizing-modus-ponens">
        <title>A symbolized argument</title>
        <statement>
          <p>If the storm reaches campus before noon, afternoon labs will be canceled.</p>
          <p>The storm will reach campus before noon.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> Afternoon labs will be canceled.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Let:
      </p>
      <p><m>S</m> = The storm reaches campus before noon.</p>
      <p><m>L</m> = Afternoon labs will be canceled.</p>
      <p>
        Symbolized:
      </p>
      <p>P1: <m>S \supset L</m></p>
      <p>P2: <m>S</m></p>
      <p><m>\therefore</m> C: <m>L</m></p>
      <p>
        This is the form we previewed much earlier: modus ponens.
        Later, the proof system will let us derive <m>L</m> from
        <m>S \supset L</m> and <m>S</m> by rule. For now, the important
        skill is recognizing and symbolizing the structure.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-symbolization-keys">
      <title>Good symbolization keys</title>
      <p>
        A good symbolization key assigns one letter to one complete
        statement. Keep the statement letters stable throughout the
        problem.
      </p>
      <p>
        Bad key:
      </p>
      <p><m>P</m> = policy</p>
      <p>
        Better key:
      </p>
      <p><m>P</m> = The policy passes.</p>
      <p>
        Bad key:
      </p>
      <p><m>R</m> = rain</p>
      <p>
        Better key:
      </p>
      <p><m>R</m> = It rains tonight.</p>
      <p>
        The symbolic letter stands for a statement that can be true
        or false, not for a topic, object, or isolated noun.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-translation-and-charity">
      <title>Translation and charity</title>
      <p>
        Symbolization is a kind of reconstruction. Sometimes the
        English is loose, compressed, or rhetorically loaded. Your
        job is to preserve the logical structure without improving
        the argument.
      </p>
      <p>
        If a passage says <q>The proposal is reckless and unpopular,
        so the council should reject it,</q> sentential logic can
        represent the conjunction in the premise:
      </p>
      <p><m>R \cdot U</m></p>
      <p>
        But sentential logic by itself does not supply the missing
        principle connecting recklessness and unpopularity to
        rejection. As in earlier chapters, reconstruction and
        evaluation remain distinct. Symbolization makes structure
        visible; it does not make unsupported leaps disappear.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-8-5-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Symbolize something you actually heard</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a short argument from your day — a conversation,
          something you read online, a news clip — that uses at
          least one conditional, disjunction, or conjunction. Write
          the argument in standard form in English, create a
          symbolization key, and translate it into symbolic notation.
          Note any places where the English was ambiguous about which
          connective was intended.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-symbolizing-where-headed">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <p>
      This chapter gives us the language of sentential logic. The
      next step is to give that language a precise method of
      evaluation. Truth tables will let us test single statements,
      pairs of statements, and whole arguments by considering every
      possible assignment of truth values to the sentence letters.
    </p>
    <p>
      After truth tables, we will turn to natural deduction. Truth
      tables tell us whether an argument is valid or invalid. Natural
      deduction can only show us how the conclusion follows from the
      premises, step by step, using rules such as Modus Ponens,
      Modus Tollens, Disjunctive Syllogism, and Hypothetical
      Syllogism; it only works for valid arguments. 
    </p>

  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch8">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced the symbolic language of sentential
      logic. The core ideas, section by section:
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>The Basic Idea (§8.1).</alert> Sentential logic treats
      whole statements as units and studies how they are joined by
      logical connectives. Simple statements are represented by
      capital sentence letters.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>The Five Connectives (§8.2).</alert> The five
      connectives are negation (<c>~</c>), conjunction (<m>\cdot</m>),
      disjunction (<m>\lor</m>), conditional (<m>\supset</m>), and
      biconditional (<m>\equiv</m>).
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Main Connective and Scope (§8.3).</alert> Parentheses
      determine the structure of compound statements. The main
      connective governs the whole statement; the scope of a
      connective is the part of the formula it controls.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Conditionals in English (§8.4).</alert> <q>If,</q>
      <q>only if,</q> <q>if and only if,</q> <q>unless,</q> and
      <q>neither/nor</q> require special care in translation.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Symbolizing Arguments (§8.5).</alert> Arguments should
      be put in standard form and symbolized with a clear key. A
      sentence letter stands for a complete statement, not for a
      noun or topic.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Where We're Headed (§8.6).</alert> The next chapter
      uses truth tables to evaluate symbolic statements and
      arguments.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch8-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-antecedent">
        <title>Antecedent</title>
        <p>The left side of a conditional; in <m>P \supset Q</m>, <m>P</m> is the antecedent. (§8.2, §8.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-biconditional">
        <title>Biconditional</title>
        <p>A compound statement of the form <m>P \equiv Q</m>, read <q><m>P</m> if and only if <m>Q</m>.</q> (§8.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-compound-statement">
        <title>Compound statement</title>
        <p>A statement built from one or more simpler statements using logical connectives. (§8.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-conjunction">
        <title>Conjunction</title>
        <p>A compound statement of the form <m>P \cdot Q</m>, read <q><m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>.</q> (§8.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-connective">
        <title>Connective</title>
        <p>A logical operator used to build compound statements from simpler statements. (§8.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-consequent">
        <title>Consequent</title>
        <p>The right side of a conditional; in <m>P \supset Q</m>, <m>Q</m> is the consequent. (§8.2, §8.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-conditional">
        <title>Conditional</title>
        <p>A compound statement of the form <m>P \supset Q</m>, read <q>if <m>P</m>, then <m>Q</m>.</q> (§8.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-disjunction">
        <title>Disjunction</title>
        <p>A compound statement of the form <m>P \lor Q</m>, read <q><m>P</m> or <m>Q</m>.</q> In this book, disjunction is inclusive unless specified otherwise. (§8.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-main-connective">
        <title>Main connective</title>
        <p>The connective that governs the whole compound statement. (§8.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-negation">
        <title>Negation</title>
        <p>A statement of the form <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>, read <q>not <m>P</m></q> or <q>it is not the case that <m>P</m>.</q> (§8.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-scope">
        <title>Scope</title>
        <p>The part of a formula governed by a connective. (§8.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-sentence-letter">
        <title>Sentence letter</title>
        <p>A capital letter that stands for a complete statement. (§8.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch8-simple-statement">
        <title>Simple statement</title>
        <p>A statement treated as an unanalyzed unit in sentential logic. (§8.1)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch8">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch8-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Simple and Compound Statements</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each sentence, say whether it is simple or compound
          for purposes of sentential logic. If it is compound,
          identify the main connective in English.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s01-01"><statement><p>The mayor vetoed the ordinance.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s01-02"><statement><p>The mayor vetoed the ordinance and the council scheduled an override vote.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s01-03"><statement><p>If the server restarts, then the patch installed correctly.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s01-04"><statement><p>The hearing will proceed unless the judge grants a delay.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s01-05"><statement><p>The committee did not release the report.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch8-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Symbolizing Single Statements</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use the provided symbolization key to symbolize each
          statement.
        </p>
        <p><m>P</m> = The proposal passes.</p>
        <p><m>Q</m> = The mayor signs the proposal.</p>
        <p><m>R</m> = The policy takes effect.</p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s02-01"><statement><p>The proposal passes and the mayor signs it.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s02-02"><statement><p>The proposal does not pass.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s02-03"><statement><p>If the proposal passes, then the policy takes effect.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s02-04"><statement><p>The policy takes effect only if the mayor signs the proposal.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s02-05"><statement><p>The proposal passes if and only if the mayor signs it.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s02-06"><statement><p>Neither the proposal passes nor the policy takes effect.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch8-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Main Connective and Scope</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each formula, identify the main connective. Then
          state the immediate components governed by that main
          connective.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s03-01"><statement><p><m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s03-02"><statement><p><m>P \cdot (Q \supset R)</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s03-03"><statement><p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \lor Q)</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s03-04"><statement><p><m>(P \supset Q) \equiv ({\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}P)</m></p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s03-05"><statement><p><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor (Q \cdot R)</m></p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch8-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Conditionals in English</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Symbolize each sentence. Do so in the finest-grained way possible. Create your own clear
          symbolization key. 
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s04-01"><statement><p>If the alarm sounds, the building will be evacuated.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s04-02"><statement><p>The building will be evacuated if the alarm sounds.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s04-03"><statement><p>The building will be evacuated only if the alarm sounds.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s04-04"><statement><p>The building will be evacuated if and only if the alarm sounds.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s04-05"><statement><p>The hearing will proceed unless the judge grants a delay.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s04-06"><statement><p>The grant will be renewed only if the report is submitted on time.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch8-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Symbolizing Arguments</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Put each argument in standard form, create a
          symbolization key, and symbolize the argument.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s05-01"><statement><p>If the storm reaches campus before noon, afternoon labs will be canceled. The storm will reach campus before noon. Therefore, afternoon labs will be canceled.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s05-02"><statement><p>If the city raises the property tax rate, school revenue will increase. School revenue will not increase. Therefore, the city will not raise the property tax rate.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s05-03"><statement><p>Either the proposal cleared committee or the chair tabled it. The proposal did not clear committee. So, the chair tabled it.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s05-04"><statement><p>If the software collects sensitive data, then it creates privacy risks. If it creates privacy risks, then the university should require review. Therefore, if the software collects sensitive data, then the university should require review.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch8-s06">
      <title>Exercise Set 6: Mixed Translation</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Symbolize each sentence or argument. Watch for main
          connective, scope, and conditional direction.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s06-01"><statement><p>The council will approve the budget only if the revenue forecast improves and the public hearing goes smoothly.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s06-02"><statement><p>If the model is accurate, then either the forecast improves or the old assumptions were wrong.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s06-03"><statement><p>It is not the case that both the committee met and the proposal advanced.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s06-04"><statement><p>The archive opens to researchers if and only if the donor agreement is signed and the catalog is complete.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-s06-05"><statement><p>Unless the server is repaired, the site will stay offline and students will miss the deadline.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch8-writing">
      <title>Writing Prompt</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          This prompt connects to Field Exercise 8-1.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch8-writing-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to the argument you symbolized in Field Exercise
            8-1. What, if anything, got lost in translation? Did the
            symbolic version capture everything the original speaker
            meant, or did the process of symbolization strip away
            something important — tone, emphasis, implied meaning?
            Write a short reflection on what sentential logic can and
            cannot preserve about ordinary reasoning.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
